{{Infobox organization | name = American Society for Cybernetics (ASC) | logo = | type = Professional Organization | founded_date = 1964 | founder = | location = [[Washington DC]], United States | origins = | key_people = [[Michael Lissack]] (current president), [[Ranulph Glanville]] (past president) | area_served = USA, worldwide | focus = [[Cybernetics]] | method = Conferences, Publications, Website. | revenue = | endowment = | num_volunteers = | num_employees = | num_members = | owner = | Non-profit_slogan = | homepage = [http://www.asc-cybernetics.org/ homepage] | tax_exempt = | dissolved = | footnotes = }}
The '''American Society for Cybernetics''' ('''ASC''') is an American non-profit [[school|scholastic]] [[organization]] for the advancement of [[cybernetics]] as a [[science]] and the interdisciplinary collaboration and synthesis of cybernetics. The society contributes to the cooperation around the research and development of cybernetics methods and techniques to manage [[complex systems]].<ref>[http://www.asc-cybernetics.org/organization/constitution.htm ASC CONSTITUTION]. Retrieved 8 June 2008.</ref>
In order to do so it holds conferences and seminars, and maintains contacts with cyberneticians and organizations for cybernetics in other countries. Further activities of the ASC are: * ASC Glossary on Cybernetics and Systems Theory<ref>[http://pespmc1.vub.ac.be/ASC/ASCGloss.html ASC Glossary]. Retrieved 8 June 2008.</ref> * Disciplinary Matrices in Cybernetics and Systems Science<ref name="gwu.edu">[http://www.gwu.edu/~asc/people/dpmatrix.html Disciplinary Matrices in Cybernetics and Systems Science]. Retrieved 8 June 2008.</ref> * Wiener and McCulloch awards
The American Society for Cybernetics was founded in 1964 in [[Washington, DC]] to encourage new developments in cybernetics as an interdisciplinary field with [[Warren McCulloch]] as first elected president of the ASC.<ref>[http://www.asc-cybernetics.org/organization/history.htm HISTORY OF THE ASC]. Retrieved 8 June 2008.</ref> In the 1980s ASC became a member of the [[International Federation for Systems Research]], and begin 1990s supported the [[Principia Cybernetica]] Project. Since 1995 the home office for the ASC is located at the [[George Washington University]].
The ASC has been maintaining an editorial column in the interdisciplinary ''[[Cybernetics and Human Knowing|Cybernetics and Human Knowing Journal]]'' since its first issue in 1992. Rodney Donaldson was the first ASC president to write for the column.
