In [[mathematics]], a '''continuum structure function (CSF)''' is defined by [[Laurence Baxter]] as a nondecreasing [[map (mathematics)|map]]ping from the unit [[hypercube]] to the unit [[interval (mathematics)|interval]]. It is used by Baxter to help in the [[Mathematical model]]ling of the level of performance of a system in terms of the performance levels of its components.<ref>Baxter, L A (1984) Continuum structures I., ''Journal of Applied Probability'', 21 (4), pp. 802–815 {{jstor|3213697}}</ref><ref>Baxter, L A, (1986), Continuum structures. II, ''Math. Proc. Camb. Phil. Soc''.99, 331 331</ref><ref>Kim, Chul; Baxter, Laurence A.(1987) Reliability importance for continuum structure functions. ''Journal of Applied Probability'', 24, 779–785 {{jstor|10.2307/3214108}}</ref>

