In mathematics,  '''Jacob's ladder''' is a surface with infinite [[Genus (mathematics)|genus]] and two ends. It was  named after [[Jacob's ladder]] by Étienne {{harvtxt|Ghys|1995|loc=Théorème A}},  because the surface can be constructed as the boundary of a ladder that is infinitely long in both directions.

